MABES v4.0: Mars Autonomous Bio-Engineering System

An AI-Driven Closed-Loop Architecture for Engineered Microbial Oxygen Generation on Mars

Ouadi  Maakoul — Independent Research
Final PhD Manuscript — April 2026

---

Abstract

This dissertation proposes MABES (Mars Autonomous Bio-Engineering System), a hybrid architecture integrating artificial intelligence, automated robotic biofoundries, and synthetic biology to autonomously design, construct, optimize, and deploy engineered microorganisms capable of surviving Martian environmental conditions and contributing to atmospheric oxygen production. MABES adapts the established terrestrial Design–Build–Test–Learn (DBTL) autonomous biofoundry paradigm to an interplanetary context through five specific architectural innovations: (1) latency-tolerant fully autonomous orchestration designed around the 6–48 minute Earth-Mars communication constraint, experimentally validated in ground-based latency-simulated DBTL demonstrations; (2) perchlorate soil detoxification as a mandatory biological prerequisite phase integrated within the same autonomous system, with kinetics now quantified under Martian temperature and UV conditions; (3) a three-strain synthetic consortium with explicit division of metabolic labor — oxygen production, nitrogen fixation, and soil remediation — stabilized by inter-strain orthogonal obligate commensalism, experimentally validated in cyanobacterial consortia; (4) a formal biological-electrochemical ISRU integration framework with quantitative energetic trade-space analysis; and (5) a two-phase genetic engineering strategy employing fast-growing tractable cyanobacterial chassis for Earth validation before transfer of validated modifications to Mars-deployment extremophile chassis, de-risked by recent demonstration of direct CRISPR-Cas12a editing in Chroococcidiopsis.

Target organisms are Chroococcidiopsis sp. CCMEE 029, Anabaena cylindrica UTAD A212, and an engineered Bacillus subtilis 168 derivative carrying the pcrABCD-cld perchlorate reduction pathway. A site selection framework is provided based on newly available orbital nitrate distribution maps and subsurface ice data. Multi-layer biocontainment comprises six independent mechanisms: physical containment, synthetic auxotrophy, UV-activated kill switch, quorum-sensing kill switch, orthogonal obligate commensalism, and genetic barcoding with environmental monitoring. Quantitative milestones, a bottom-up power budget validated against recent Kilopower operational data, updated dust storm contingency planning based on revised insolation reduction estimates, partial-gravity bioreactor fluid dynamics mitigation strategies, and a NASA TRL-mapped deployment roadmap incorporating the latest COSPAR planetary protection policy developments are provided. The goal is not planetary-scale terraforming, but the first demonstration of a self-improving, autonomously managed biological manufacturing system operating on an extraterrestrial body — a milestone that would represent a foundational achievement in both synthetic biology and space exploration.

