1. Introduction and Scientific Motivation

1.1 The Oxygen Economy of a Mars Base

The establishment of a sustained human presence on Mars confronts a fundamental resource asymmetry that has no terrestrial analog. The Martian atmosphere is composed of approximately 95% carbon dioxide, 1.9% molecular nitrogen, and 1.9% argon, with trace gases including carbon monoxide (~800 ppm) and water vapor. Mean surface pressure is 6–7 mbar — less than 1% of Earth's sea-level pressure — and mean surface temperature is −63°C, with diurnal excursions from approximately −80°C to +20°C in equatorial regions. Under these conditions, liquid water is thermodynamically unstable on the open surface at pressures below approximately 10 mbar, and biological processes as we understand them require engineered containment.

A six-person crewed Mars mission requires approximately 31 metric tons of liquid oxygen for the Mars Ascent Vehicle propellant oxidizer alone (Hecht et al., 2021). This figure does not include life-support oxygen for the crew during the interplanetary transit and surface stay, nor oxygen for potential surface mobility systems, medical reserves, or contingency margins. Transporting this mass from Earth's gravity well is not merely impractical — it is a hard mission constraint that makes in-situ oxygen production a prerequisite for any architecture proposing human Mars exploration beyond the Apollo-scale flags-and-footprints model.

NASA's MOXIE (Mars Oxygen In-Situ Resource Utilization Experiment) conclusively validated the electrochemical ISRU pathway. During 16 operational cycles aboard the Perseverance rover from April 2021 through mission conclusion in September 2024, MOXIE demonstrated solid-oxide CO₂ electrolysis at 800°C, producing oxygen at up to 12 g/hour at ≥98% purity — twice the original design requirement of 6 g/hour (Hecht et al., 2021, 2024). At its most productive single run, MOXIE generated 9.8 g of oxygen. Over the full mission it produced 122 g total, equivalent to the oxygen consumption of a small dog over approximately ten hours. The experiment was an unequivocal engineering success, demonstrating that electrochemical ISRU functions on the Martian surface under real environmental conditions including variable atmospheric density, dust loading, and diurnal temperature cycling.

Scaling MOXIE to mission requirements demands approximately a 200× increase in capacity. A human-scale MOXIE-derivative system would weigh approximately one metric ton and require 25–30 kWe of continuous electrical power (Hecht et al., 2024). This is achievable within projected nuclear fission surface power system capabilities. But electrochemical ISRU operates at fixed thermodynamic efficiency, requires high-temperature operation (800°C) with attendant materials challenges including seal degradation and thermal cycling fatigue, and cannot self-replicate, adapt to changing conditions, or improve its performance over time without human engineering intervention.

Biological oxygen production through oxygenic photosynthesis offers a fundamentally different energy and materials logic. Photosynthetic organisms consume local resources — atmospheric CO₂, water, and minerals from regolith — and convert them into biomass and oxygen using solar photons as the energy source. A biological system replicates exponentially from a gram-scale seed stock, adapts through natural selection augmented by directed genetic engineering, and produces oxygen as a metabolic byproduct of carbon fixation. The initial mass investment is orders of magnitude lower than any chemical alternative. The tradeoffs are complexity, timescale to reach productive capacity, and biological risk — including genetic instability, contamination, and planetary protection obligations.

MABES does not argue that biology replaces electrochemistry for Mars oxygen production. It argues that these paradigms are complementary across a defined temporal and functional division of labor:

· Electrochemical ISRU (MOXIE-class systems) addresses mission-critical near-term oxygen demands during Years 1–5 of surface operations, providing predictable, high-purity oxygen for ascent vehicle propellant and initial life support.
· Biological ISRU (MABES) addresses the sustained long-term oxygen economy from Years 5 onward, producing oxygen at fundamentally higher energetic efficiency once biological populations reach productive scale, and providing a self-improving, self-replicating manufacturing capacity that electrochemical systems cannot match.

This complementarity is formalized through a quantitative trade-space analysis presented in Section 3.

1.2 The Autonomous Biofoundry Revolution on Earth

Concurrent with advances in Mars ISRU, terrestrial synthetic biology is undergoing a fundamental transformation from manual, artisan-scale genetic engineering to AI-driven autonomous biofoundry platforms. This transformation provides the technological foundation upon which MABES is built.

The BioAutomata platform (HamediRad et al., 2019) demonstrated that a machine learning algorithm integrated with a robotic biofoundry could autonomously decide which experiments to run, execute liquid-handling and culture protocols, collect phenotypic data, and iteratively optimize organism performance without human intervention in the experimental loop. The system identified a mutant E. coli strain producing 1.77× higher lycopene titer than random sampling would have achieved in the same number of experiments.

Subsequent platforms have substantially extended this capability. A generalized platform integrating protein language models (ESM-2, ProtTrans) with automated biofoundry hardware achieved a 90-fold improvement in enzyme substrate preference and a 16-fold improvement in catalytic activity with no human operator in the decision loop (Kim et al., 2025). The 2026 AI-native biofoundry architecture using large language model-based agent systems and the Model Context Protocol (MCP) demonstrates that natural language specifications can now orchestrate entire DBTL cycles across heterogeneous laboratory hardware, bridging what the authors term "abstract scientific intent" and "heterogeneous hardware execution" (Zhang et al., 2026).

The global biofoundry ecosystem now includes platforms with mature operational capabilities: the Edinburgh Genome Foundry, iBioFAB at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, the Global Biofoundry Alliance's standardized workflows for interoperable operations (Kim et al., 2025), Ginkgo Bioworks' Reconfigurable Automation Cart (RAC) for high-throughput organism engineering, and numerous academic and commercial facilities worldwide. A recent OECD technology assessment characterizes autonomous biofoundries as a transformative technology with potential applications spanning pharmaceuticals, agriculture, materials science, and environmental remediation (OECD, 2025).

The question MABES asks is: what does this paradigm require to function on another planet?

1.3 The Four Gaps: Why Terrestrial Platforms Cannot Simply Be Transplanted to Mars

Existing autonomous biofoundry platforms operate under four assumptions that fail catastrophically in the Martian context. MABES addresses each as a first-class architectural constraint.

Gap 1 — Human Oversight Assumption: All documented terrestrial DBTL platforms operate with a human-in-the-loop for experiment approval, failure diagnosis, reagent inventory management, and safety response. Even the most autonomous systems (BioAutomata, the AI-native biofoundry) contact human operators when encountering unexpected results outside pre-programmed parameter ranges. On Mars, the Earth-Mars communication latency — ranging from approximately 3 minutes at closest approach to 24 minutes at greatest separation, yielding a round-trip signal delay of 6–48 minutes — makes real-time human supervision of any process operating on sub-hour timescales operationally impossible. More critically, if a bioreactor shows signs of containment breach, waiting 6–48 minutes for human authorization to initiate a lockdown is unacceptable from both safety and planetary protection perspectives. MABES must make all operational decisions — including safety-critical containment responses — autonomously, onboard, without Earth contact.

Gap 2 — Earth-Standard Laboratory Conditions: Terrestrial biofoundries operate in temperature-controlled rooms (typically 20–25°C), are shielded from ionizing radiation by Earth's atmosphere and magnetosphere, operate at 1 atm pressure and 1g gravity, and have effectively unlimited access to electrical power from the grid. A Mars-deployed biofoundry faces Martian diurnal temperature swings of up to 100°C even within a thermally managed habitat, chronic ionizing radiation of 0.2–0.3 Gy/day from galactic cosmic rays and solar energetic particles, 0.38g gravity with poorly characterized effects on bioreactor fluid dynamics, and operation within a pressurized module powered by a finite nuclear fission source with a total power budget of approximately 10 kWe for all habitat functions. Every subsystem must be redesigned for this environment.

Gap 3 — External Supply Chain Assumption: Terrestrial biofoundries assume regular delivery of reagents — DNA synthesis oligos, enzymes, growth media components, antibiotics, and replacement hardware — via commercial supply chains with delivery times measured in days. MABES must eventually transition to in-situ resource utilization for biological inputs: water from subsurface ice extraction, mineral nutrients from detoxified Martian regolith, and atmospheric CO₂ and N₂ as carbon and nitrogen feedstocks. The initial seed stock and a finite reagent cache will be launched from Earth, but sustained operation requires closing resource loops.

Gap 4 — No Planetary Protection Obligation: Terrestrial platforms operate in controlled laboratory environments with no risk of contaminating a pristine planetary body or interfering with the search for extant life. MABES must operate under COSPAR Planetary Protection Category IV constraints for Mars lander missions, with the ethical and scientific imperative to prevent forward contamination of any environment where Martian life might exist. This constraint is not merely procedural — it is a design driver that shapes the entire containment architecture.

These four gaps define the engineering problem space. MABES addresses each specifically through its architecture, as detailed in Section 5.

