Interpretation of the trade-space:

MOXIE-class electrochemical systems dominate the trade-space in Years 1–5 of surface operations because they deliver validated, predictable, high-purity oxygen production from day one of deployment. There is no biological ramp-up period — the system operates at its design capacity as soon as power is applied. This is essential for mission-critical oxygen demands, particularly the accumulation of liquid oxygen propellant for the ascent vehicle.

MABES operates in parallel during this period. Phase 1 bioreactors are established, and the autonomous DBTL system begins optimization cycles. The biological population expands exponentially from the initial seed stock, with doubling times of ≤72 hours (Phase 1 target) yielding approximately 10–15 doublings per Earth year. The O₂ production rate is initially negligible but grows as population scales.

The handoff begins in Years 3–5 as MABES Phase 2 ecological chambers scale to areas of 500–2,000 m². At 25 g/m²/day, a 1,000 m² chamber produces 25 kg O₂/day — a meaningful supplement to life-support oxygen budgets for a crew of 6 (which consume approximately 5–6 kg O₂/day). By Year 8+, MABES Phase 3 organisms — optimized through hundreds of autonomous DBTL cycles with Mars-specific selection — are producing oxygen at energetic efficiencies that electrochemical systems cannot approach, because sunlight is free and the organisms are self-replicating capital.

The critical unknown is how quickly biological O₂ production rate can scale under autonomous AI-driven optimization. This is the central empirical question that Phase 0 (Earth validation) and Phase 1 (Mars demonstration) of MABES must answer. The answer will determine the slope of the biological production curve and thus the timing of the handoff point.

