4. Biological Agents: Candidate Organisms and Genetic Engineering Strategy

4.1 Selection Criteria

Candidate organisms for MABES deployment are selected on five criteria:

1. Demonstrated survival in Mars-simulated laboratory conditions (low pressure, low temperature, radiation exposure, desiccation) or actual space exposure (LEO experiments).
2. Genetic tractability for CRISPR-based genome engineering, including established protocols for transformation, selection, and genome editing.
3. Capacity for CO₂ fixation and O₂ production via oxygenic photosynthesis, with characterized photosynthetic efficiency under relevant conditions.
4. Tolerance to at least one primary Mars stressor (ionizing radiation, desiccation, perchlorate, cold, UV) that can be enhanced or combined through engineering.
5. Co-engineering potential for consortium-level functions: nitrogen fixation (for Strain B) or perchlorate reduction (for Strain C).

4.2 Mars-Deployment Chassis Organisms

Strain A — Primary O₂ Producer: Chroococcidiopsis sp. CCMEE 029

Chroococcidiopsis is a unicellular desert cyanobacterium of the order Chroococcidiopsidales, found in hypolithic (under-rock) communities in the Atacama Desert, the Dry Valleys of Antarctica, and other extreme arid environments. It is the most thoroughly space-tested photosynthetic microorganism.

· Space exposure heritage: Exposed to low Earth orbit for 1.5 years during the BIOMEX experiment aboard the ISS. Survived and recovered photosynthetic function upon rehydration (Billi et al., 2019). Post-flight whole-genome sequencing showed no increased mutation rate (Napoli et al., 2022).
· Desiccation tolerance: Survives complete dehydration for months to years, with genomic integrity maintained. This is critical for launch as dried spore stocks, which are stable at room temperature for extended periods.
· Radiation resistance: In the desiccated state, survives acute doses up to approximately 15 kGy. The chronic, lower-dose radiation environment of Mars is well within its tolerance envelope.
· Growth on Mars simulants: Grows on MGS-1 and MMS-2 Martian regolith simulants supplemented with minimal nutrients (Fais et al., 2024).
· Perchlorate tolerance: Exceeds baseline cyanobacterial levels; exact tolerance threshold is being characterized in ongoing studies.
· Genetic tractability: Until recently, a limitation. However, Garcia et al. (2026, in press) report the first successful CRISPR-Cas12a-based genome editing in Chroococcidiopsis sp. CCMEE 029, achieving 12% knockout efficiency and 4% knock-in efficiency via electroporation of pre-assembled ribonucleoprotein complexes. This demonstration substantially de-risks direct engineering of the Mars-deployment chassis.

Strain B — Nitrogen Fixer and Secondary O₂ Producer: Anabaena cylindrica UTAD A212

Anabaena cylindrica is a filamentous cyanobacterium of the order Nostocales, distinguished by the presence of heterocysts — specialized, terminally differentiated cells that provide a microaerobic environment for the oxygen-sensitive nitrogenase enzyme complex.

· Nitrogen fixation: Heterocysts fix atmospheric N₂ to NH₃ using ATP and reductant supplied by adjacent vegetative cells. The NH₃ is exported to the filament and becomes bioavailable nitrogen for the entire consortium.
· Simultaneous O₂ production: Vegetative cells perform oxygenic photosynthesis concurrently with nitrogen fixation in heterocysts. This spatial compartmentalization resolves the oxygen sensitivity of nitrogenase.
· Growth on Mars simulants: Macário et al. (2025) demonstrated growth of Anabaena cylindrica on MGS-1 and MMS-2 Martian regolith simulants in soluble extract form, showing that regolith contains sufficient mineral nutrients for short-term cyanobacterial growth.
· Genetic tractability: A 2025 study (ACS Synthetic Biology) reports CRISPR-Cas12a-based genome editing of the closely related Anabaena sp. PCC 7120, providing the genetic toolkit for Strain B modification.

Strain C Base — Soil Interaction: Desmonostoc muscorum UTAD N213

Desmonostoc muscorum (formerly Nostoc muscorum) is a filamentous cyanobacterium with demonstrated UV-B resistance specifically when protected by Martian clay minerals.

· Clay-shielding interaction: Macário et al. (2025) showed that Desmonostoc survival under UV-B radiation is significantly enhanced when the cells are associated with montmorillonite and nontronite clays — both phyllosilicates present in Martian regolith. This interaction is highly relevant for Phase 3 surface deployment, where clay mineral layers may provide natural UV attenuation for biofilm communities.
· The Strain C chassis for perchlorate reduction (below) is a Bacillus subtilis derivative, but the clay-shielding biology of Desmonostoc informs Phase 3 biofilm protection strategies.

Strain C — Soil Remediation: Engineered Bacillus subtilis 168 with pcrABCD-cld

Bacillus subtilis strain 168 is chosen as the chassis for perchlorate reduction based on:

· Spaceflight heritage: Used in the Tardigrade Dsup expression experiments aboard the ISS; demonstrates robust growth in space-relevant conditions.
· Established CRISPR toolkit: One of the most thoroughly characterized Gram-positive model organisms for genetic engineering.
· Spore formation: Like Chroococcidiopsis, B. subtilis forms durable spores that can survive launch and interplanetary transit in a dried state.
· Engineered pathway: The pcrABCD (perchlorate reductase) and cld (chlorite dismutase) gene cluster from Pseudomonas stutzeri or Azospira oryzae will be transferred to B. subtilis 168 under a constitutive, cold-active promoter. The biochemical pathway is: ClO₄⁻ → ClO₃⁻ → ClO₂⁻ → Cl⁻ + O₂. The reaction produces molecular oxygen as a byproduct, which is captured and routed to the habitat life support system.

Strain C is deployed only in the sealed Soil Detoxification Module (Section 5.4) and carries the most stringent biocontainment features because it is designed to interact directly with Martian regolith.

4.3 Two-Phase Genetic Engineering Strategy

Direct engineering of Chroococcidiopsis and Anabaena — slow-growing extremophiles with doubling times of days rather than hours — creates unnecessary development friction during Earth validation. MABES adopts a two-phase genetic strategy that decouples rapid iteration from final chassis validation.

Phase A — Rapid Development Chassis (Earth Validation): Synechocystis sp. PCC 6803 and Synechococcus sp.

These model cyanobacteria serve as the primary chassis for Earth DBTL cycles. Their advantages:

· Doubling time: Approximately 7 hours for Synechocystis, 3–4 hours for Synechococcus, versus ~4 days for Chroococcidiopsis. This enables ~14× faster DBTL cycling.
· Established CRISPR tools:
  · CRISPRa (CRISPR activation) in Synechocystis enables multiplexed upregulation of endogenous and heterologous targets (Communications Biology, 2025).
  · Genome-wide CRISPRi (CRISPR interference) screens in Synechococcus have identified subtle genetic modifications improving growth under temperature and light extremes (PNAS, 2025).
· Validated metabolic models: Genome-scale metabolic models for both organisms are mature and integrated with flux balance analysis tools.

During Phase 0, the AI Core generates candidate genetic modifications — promoter sequences, gene inserts, regulatory circuits, pathway architectures — and validates them in the fast chassis. Promising constructs that improve fitness metrics (O₂ production, radiation tolerance, cold adaptation) are advanced to Phase B.

Phase B — Mars-Deployment Chassis Transfer

Validated genetic modifications are transferred to the Mars-deployment chassis:

· For Chroococcidiopsis: Shuttle vectors and conjugation protocols established for interspecies cyanobacterial gene transfer. The recent demonstration of direct CRISPR-Cas12a editing (Garcia et al., 2026) provides an alternative pathway if transfer proves inefficient.
· For Anabaena: CRISPR-Cas12a methods validated in Anabaena sp. PCC 7120 are adapted for A. cylindrica UTAD A212.
· For B. subtilis 168: Standard Bacillus transformation protocols for the pcrABCD-cld pathway.

The slower development cycle of the Mars-deployment chassis is acceptable at this stage because the genetic architecture has already been validated in the fast chassis. This two-phase strategy reduces total Earth validation timeline by an estimated 60–70% compared to developing exclusively in the slow chassis.

