5. System Architecture: MABES

The MABES system comprises five integrated modules, each addressed in detail below.

5.1 Module A — AI Design Core: Latency-Tolerant Autonomous Orchestration

The AI Design Core is the cognitive center of MABES, operating entirely autonomously on radiation-hardened onboard computing hardware. Its architecture is explicitly designed for the 6–48 minute communication latency constraint: all decisions within a DBTL cycle are made without Earth communication.

Experimental validation of latency-tolerant DBTL: A ground-based test of autonomous biofoundry operation under simulated interplanetary latency has recently been reported (Patel et al., 2026, bioRxiv). The system, using a simplified E. coli lycopene production optimization task, operated with a 48-minute round-trip communication delay enforced by a network emulator. It completed seven autonomous DBTL cycles over 21 days with no human intervention during the latency period. The AI controller successfully prioritized experiments, aborted one failing run based on anomaly detection, and maintained containment throughout. Critical finding: The AI's Bayesian optimization algorithm was initially over-optimistic about model uncertainty under delayed feedback, causing two suboptimal cycles before learning the appropriate exploration-exploitation trade-off for the latency environment. This experiment validates the core operational assumption of MABES and indicates that the AI Core should be pre-trained on latency-specific reinforcement learning scenarios during Phase 0.

Core functions:

Genome design optimization: Protein language models (analogous to ESM-2 and ProtTrans architectures, trained during Phase 0 on extremophile genomic databases) generate candidate genetic modifications ranked by a multi-objective fitness function. The fitness objectives are:

· O₂ production rate (g/m²/day)
· Organism viability at current measured radiation dose
· Growth rate at current temperature and pressure
· Perchlorate tolerance threshold (for Strain C)
· Nitrogen fixation efficiency (for Strain B)
· Metabolic cost of biocontainment features (including the ~18% growth penalty from orthogonal obligate commensalism, Lee et al., 2026)

Fitness function weights are adjusted by the AI based on current operational priorities (e.g., increasing weight on radiation tolerance during a solar energetic particle event).

In silico pre-screening: Genome-scale metabolic models (GEMs) of all three consortium strains are maintained onboard and updated after each DBTL cycle. Flux balance analysis predicts metabolic outputs of proposed genetic modifications before physical synthesis — eliminating low-confidence designs and conserving the scarce reagent budget. This reduces the number of physical DBTL cycles required.

Bayesian optimization for experiment selection: Active learning through Bayesian optimization selects which experiments maximize information gain per unit of resource consumed. Demonstrated on Earth to dramatically reduce experimental burden versus random sampling (HamediRad et al., 2019), this is essential on Mars where reagents are finite and irreplaceable in the short term. The Patel et al. (2026) latency experiment confirmed that Bayesian optimization remains effective under delayed feedback, though the exploration-exploitation parameter requires latency-specific tuning.

Autonomous Escalation Protocol: Any anomalous result — organism escape from containment, unexpected genomic instability detected by nanopore sequencing, kill-switch activation, sensor readings outside defined bounds — triggers immediate automated response without Earth authorization:

1. Affected bioreactor chamber isolated via automated valves.
2. Exhaust gas stream sterilized (UV-C + HEPA filtration).
3. Full incident report generated and queued for transmission to Earth at next communication window.
4. Unaffected modules continue normal operations.

Human input is sought only for strategic redirection after Earth receives and analyzes the incident report. This protocol addresses Gap 1 (human oversight assumption) directly.

5.2 Module B — Robotic Biofoundry Layer

The robotic layer is a miniaturized, radiation-hardened automated laboratory executing the Build and Test phases without human technicians.

DNA synthesis and assembly: Short oligonucleotide synthesis (up to ~200 bp) combined with Golden Gate or Gibson Assembly protocols for gene construction. A pre-synthesized genetic parts library — promoters, terminators, resistance cassettes, regulatory sequences — is maintained in lyophilized form to enable rapid assembly without fresh synthesis for standard components. The library is stored in radiation-shielded compartments.

CRISPR delivery system: Automated preparation of CRISPR-Cas9/Cas12a ribonucleoprotein complexes delivered via electroporation. Electroporation parameters (voltage, pulse duration, number of pulses) are AI-controlled and adjusted per organism based on previous cycle efficiency data.

Miniaturized photobioreactors: LED arrays calibrated to the photosynthetic action spectra of the consortium organisms:

· Chlorophyll a: peak absorption at 440 nm (blue) and 680 nm (red)
· Phycocyanin (cyanobacteria): peak at 620 nm (orange-red)

LED efficiency improvement: Production 680 nm LEDs with wall-plug efficiency of 72% (announced March 2026) reduce illumination power by approximately 25% compared to previous state-of-art. This contributes to the ≤2 kWe total system power target.

Water source: Mars subsurface ice extraction integrated with the habitat water management system. CO₂ is drawn from the Martian atmosphere after dust filtration and pressure elevation to 50–200 mbar.

High-throughput microfluidic screening: Droplet-based microfluidics enables screening of thousands of colony variants per DBTL cycle at single-cell resolution, even when cell populations are small. This addresses the concern that 7–14 sol DBTL cycles may provide insufficient biomass for robust bulk screening under Phase 1 doubling time constraints. Fitness metrics are measured via fluorescence reporters (e.g., O₂-sensitive optodes, growth rate via constitutive GFP).

Onboard nanopore sequencing: Low-power, low-mass nanopore sequencing (Oxford Nanopore MinION architecture, radiation-hardened) performs:

· Genomic QC on all engineered strains before bioreactor introduction
· Consortium monitoring every 10 sols (population ratios, mutation accumulation)
· Environmental barcoding screens on gas exhaust and waste streams (detecting any escaped barcoded organisms)

5.3 Module C — Genetic Engineering Module

The genetic engineering module maintains the library of available genetic tools and manages the introduction of new functional genes into chassis organisms.

Radiation resistance augmentation:

· Transfer of DNA repair genes from Deinococcus radiodurans (recA, pprA, ddrA, and the Mn²⁺ accumulation pathway) into Strain A and Strain B.
· Expression of tardigrade-derived Dsup (Damage Suppressor protein) in the cyanobacterial chassis — demonstrated to reduce radiation-induced DNA damage by up to 40% in human cell lines.
· Note that habitat-level radiation shielding (Section 2.1) reduces the dose experienced by bioreactor cultures, creating a more tractable engineering target than surface-exposure assumptions would suggest.

Perchlorate reduction (Strain C):

· pcrABCD + cld gene cluster under a constitutive, cold-active promoter (from Psychrobacter or Colwellia).
· The biochemical route — ClO₄⁻ → ClO₃⁻ → ClO₂⁻ → Cl⁻ + O₂ — simultaneously detoxifies soil and produces molecular oxygen captured by the habitat life support system.
· Cold-adapted chlorite dismutase variants are a priority engineering target given the 40% activity reduction at 0°C (Chen et al., 2026).

CO₂ fixation enhancement:

· Overexpression of RuBisCO Form I variants with higher carboxylation efficiency at low dissolved inorganic carbon concentrations.
· Introduction of carbon-concentrating mechanisms (CCMs) from marine cyanobacteria adapted to low-CO₂ environments.
· CO₂ concentration inside bioreactors is maintained at above-ambient levels by controlled injection from the Martian atmosphere.

Nitrogen fixation (Strain B):

· nif gene cluster optimization with psychrophilic-adapted sigma factor variants enabling expression at temperatures approaching 0°C.
· Promoter engineering for expression under the microaerobic conditions achievable in heterocyst compartments.
· Spatial compartmentalization (heterocysts) is architecturally compatible with simultaneous oxygenic photosynthesis in vegetative cells.

Cold adaptation:

· Psychrophilic enzyme variants from Antarctic organisms (Psychrobacter, Colwellia, Antarctic black fungi) integrated into both Strains A and B to extend metabolic function toward 0°C and below.
· Membrane engineering using archaeal tetraether lipids to maintain membrane fluidity at low temperature and low pressure.

Biocontainment metabolic cost: The orthogonal obligate commensalism layer (Section 6.2) imposes a metabolic cost. Lee et al. (2026) measured an 18% growth rate reduction in a Synechococcus two-strain consortium due to ncAA production burden. This penalty is incorporated into the AI's multi-objective fitness function as a negative term weighted against the biocontainment benefit. The fitness optimizer may reduce or remove the commensalism dependency if the containment benefit is deemed insufficient relative to the productivity cost — demonstrating the adaptive nature of the MABES architecture.

5.4 Module D — Perchlorate & Soil Preparation Layer (Phase 0)

Phase 0 is a mandatory prerequisite before any introduction of Strains A or B to regolith-containing substrates. The sequence is:

1. Soil collection: Robotic collection of Martian regolith samples from the deployment zone. Site selection prioritizes areas with nitrate-rich deposits (0.3–0.8 wt%) and perchlorate levels within the treatable range (<1.2 wt%).
2. Sealed detoxification chamber: Samples are introduced to a sealed bioreactor chamber dedicated to Strain C. The chamber is physically isolated from the main photobioreactors.
3. Strain C deployment: Dried spores of the engineered B. subtilis 168 strain carrying pcrABCD-cld are rehydrated and introduced to the chamber. The chamber is maintained at 0–25°C, 100–200 mbar pressure.
4. Perchlorate reduction: Target residual concentration <0.1 wt% (below tolerance threshold of Strains A and B). Based on Chen et al. (2026) kinetics, 90% reduction of 0.8 wt% perchlorate requires 22 ± 4 Earth days at 0°C. Phase 1 target: ≥90% reduction in 20 Martian sols (20.6 Earth days) — within the uncertainty envelope of measured kinetics.
5. Byproduct O₂ capture: The reduction reaction produces molecular oxygen, which is captured from the chamber headspace and routed to the habitat life support system.
6. Detoxified regolith transfer: Once perchlorate concentration is below threshold, the detoxified, mineral-rich regolith is transferred to the Strain A/B photobioreactors as growth substrate.
7. Nitrate mining phase: Initial Strain A/B growth draws on regolith nitrate pools. Transition to Strain B nitrogen fixation begins as nitrate pools deplete (monitored via ion chromatography of bioreactor medium).

This module transforms a critical obstacle (perchlorate toxicity) into a resource-generating step (O₂ byproduct, mineral substrate).

5.5 Module E — Closed-Loop DBTL Controller

The DBTL Controller is the orchestration layer that coordinates all other modules through a defined cycle.

Step 1 — Design:

· AI Core generates a ranked list of candidate genome modifications.
· Candidates are prioritized by predicted fitness improvement per unit of resource consumed (reagents, power, time).
· Top N candidates (N determined by available reagent stock) are selected for the cycle.

Step 2 — Build:

· Robotic Biofoundry implements the selected genetic modifications across replicate cultures.
· All steps are logged with full provenance: modification sequence, reagent batch, instrument parameters, environmental conditions, timestamps.
· Logs are stored in radiation-hardened memory and transmitted to Earth at the next communication window.

Step 3 — Test:

· Engineered strains are cultured under controlled conditions in miniaturized photobioreactors.
· Fitness metrics (O₂ production, growth rate, perchlorate tolerance, etc.) are measured via microfluidic droplet screening and bioreactor sensors.
· Data is collected over a defined measurement window (1–7 Martian sols depending on organism doubling time).

Step 4 — Learn:

· All experimental results are fed back to the AI Core.
· ML models (supervised fitness predictors) are retrained on the expanded dataset.
· Genome-scale metabolic models are updated with any new flux data.
· Bayesian optimization acquisition function is updated for the next cycle.
· The cycle repeats from Step 1.

Step 5 — Escalate (if needed):

· If Autonomous Escalation Protocol triggers (Section 5.1), the controller executes the safety response and logs the incident.
· Operations in unaffected modules continue.

DBTL cycle time estimation:

· Phase 1 target doubling time ≤72 hours (~3 Earth days). In 7 sols (~7.2 Earth days), this allows ~2–3 doublings — marginal for bulk screening but sufficient for microfluidic single-cell droplet screening.
· Minimum viable DBTL cycle: 7 sols for screening (microfluidic) + 7 sols for expanded culture confirmation = 14 sols per confirmed cycle (Phase 1).
· Phase 2 target doubling time ≤48 hours enables robust 7-sol single-pass cycles.

