6. Planetary Protection and Biocontainment Architecture

Planetary protection is not an afterthought in MABES — it is a design constraint at every architectural level.

6.1 COSPAR Policy Compliance and Recent Developments

Mars missions carrying intentionally deployed living organisms fall under COSPAR Planetary Protection Category IV. MABES adopts Category IV-equivalent standards throughout all phases.

Recent policy developments: At the 46th COSPAR Scientific Assembly (March 2026), a dedicated session addressed "Planetary Protection for Human Missions and In-Situ Biological Resource Utilization." Key outcomes relevant to MABES (Hedman et al., 2026; COSPAR Information Bulletin, 2026):

· A new working group has been formed to develop specific guidelines for "Contained Biological ISRU Systems" on Mars, with a draft framework expected in 2027.
· Consensus emerged that pressurized habitat modules with sealed bioreactors operating at <200 mbar internal pressure and HEPA-filtered exhaust represent a "contained use" scenario that does not require a full Category IVc review, provided continuous environmental monitoring for escape is maintained and documented.
· A recommendation was adopted that any intentional release of engineered organisms beyond habitat boundaries (MABES Phase 3) requires prior peer-reviewed determination that the target zone is not a "special region" and that no extant Martian life has been detected within a 10 km radius.

Category IVc: The Category IVc designation applies to spacecraft accessing Mars "special regions" — defined as areas where liquid water may currently exist (including recurring slope lineae, subsurface ice interfaces, and potential brine environments). Phase 1 confinement to pressurized habitat modules does not trigger IVc requirements. Transition to Phase 2 ecological chambers and Phase 3 surface deployment would require updated COSPAR review, specifically addressing whether target deployment zones have been cleared as non-special regions by prior dedicated life-detection missions.

MABES position: The search for life and the engineering of life on Mars are sequential, not parallel, imperatives. Phase 2 and Phase 3 deployment requires prior scientific determination that no extant Martian life exists in target deployment zones. MABES Phase 1 and Phase 2 operations are designed to meet or exceed the anticipated COSPAR "contained use" guidelines. Phase 3 deployment will adhere to the final framework once published.

6.2 Six-Layer Biocontainment Architecture

MABES implements biocontainment at six independent layers, such that the failure of any single layer does not result in uncontrolled organism release.

Layer 1 — Physical Containment:

· All biological activity in Phases 0 and 1 occurs within sealed bioreactor vessels.
· HEPA-filtered gas exchange (0.3 μm particle removal, >99.97% efficiency).
· Redundant pressure seals with leak detection sensors.
· UV-C sterilization of all gas and liquid effluent streams (254 nm, 40 mJ/cm² dose sufficient for 4-log reduction of bacterial spores).
· No organism exits any physical enclosure without passing through a validated sterilization step.

Layer 2 — Synthetic Auxotrophy:

· All three MABES strains are engineered with dependency on one or more non-canonical amino acids (ncAAs), supplied exclusively by the MABES system.
· Without continuous ncAA supply, organisms cannot synthesize essential structural proteins.
· Programmed growth arrest followed by cell death within 2–5 doublings.
· This mechanism is chemically orthogonal to all other containment layers (ncAAs do not occur in nature).

Layer 3 — UV-Activated Kill Switch:

· Each strain carries a kill-switch circuit using a UV-responsive promoter (e.g., recA promoter from E. coli or UV-responsive elements from cyanobacteria).
· Promoter drives expression of MazF mRNA interferase, which cleaves mRNA at ACA sequences, arresting translation.
· UV flux required to activate the switch is calibrated below ambient Martian surface UV and above the maximum UV leakage from shielded bioreactor enclosures.
· If organisms escape into direct Martian surface UV, the switch activates within minutes, producing sufficient MazF to initiate programmed cell death.

Layer 4 — Quorum-Sensing Kill Switch:

· A quorum-sensing circuit (e.g., luxI/luxR system from Vibrio fischeri, adapted for cyanobacteria) monitors population density via autoinducer concentration.
· If population density falls outside a defined operational range — indicating either dispersion into a low-density open environment or population collapse — a second kill-switch circuit activates.
· This switch produces a different toxic protein (e.g., CcdB gyrase poison, which inhibits DNA gyrase and causes double-strand breaks).
· The two kill-switch circuits use orthogonal mechanisms to prevent co-failure.

Layer 5 — Orthogonal Obligate Commensalism:

· Inter-strain dependencies engineered such that no single strain can survive without the consortium.
· Strain A produces a specific ncAA or modified cofactor required by Strain B.
· Strain B produces a nitrogen compound (e.g., a specific amino acid) required by Strain C.
· Strain C produces a detoxification byproduct utilized by Strain A.
· If any single strain escapes containment, it loses access to the metabolites produced by the other two and cannot sustain growth.
· This layer has been experimentally validated in a two-strain Synechococcus consortium (Lee et al., 2026, bioRxiv v2), which maintained stable population ratios for 45 days and prevented escape of either strain in non-sterile microcosms.
· Metabolic cost: The ncAA production burden reduced growth rate by ~18% in the validated system. This penalty is incorporated into the AI's fitness function.

Layer 6 — Genetic Barcoding and Environmental Monitoring:

· All MABES strains carry unique synthetic non-coding DNA barcodes (20–25 bp sequences) inserted into neutral genomic loci.
· Barcodes are detectable by PCR with high sensitivity (<10 copies per reaction).
· Environmental monitoring includes:
  · Nanopore sequencing of gas exhaust streams (weekly)
  · PCR screening of water waste streams (weekly)
  · Periodic swabs of surfaces outside containment zones (monthly)
· Any positive detection of a MABES barcode triggers:
  1. Immediate Layer 1 lockdown of all bioreactor chambers
  2. Sterilization of exhaust streams
  3. Full incident report transmitted to Earth at next communication window
  4. Investigation protocol to identify breach source

Target escape rate: <10⁻⁹ per DBTL cycle (Phase 1), <10⁻¹² per cycle (Phase 2). These targets are consistent with pharmaceutical GMO containment standards.

