8. Deployment Roadmap: TRL-Mapped Phase Strategy with Site Selection

8.1 Site Selection Considerations for Phase 1 Deployment

While MABES is designed to operate with local resources at any landing site, the efficiency of early-phase biological operations can be improved by site selection informed by recent orbital data. MABES recommends that mission planners prioritize landing sites meeting the following criteria:

Criterion 1 — Nitrate-rich regolith: Smith et al. (2026) identify elevated near-surface nitrate concentrations (0.3–0.8 wt%) in mid-latitude sedimentary deposits. Candidate regions include:

· Northern plains (Acidalia Planitia, Utopia Planitia)
· Crater basins with sedimentary infill (Gale Crater, Jezero Crater)
· Areas within 500 km of confirmed nitrate deposits

Criterion 2 — Shallow subsurface ice: Water ice within 1–2 meters depth has been confirmed at Utopia Planitia and Arcadia Planitia by orbital radar soundings. Accessible ice reduces water transport energy and enables ISRU water supply for bioreactors.

Criterion 3 — Thermal environment: Equatorial to mid-latitude sites (0°–40° latitude) experience more moderate diurnal temperature swings, reducing thermal management power requirements.

Criterion 4 — Engineering and safety constraints: Landing site must meet all standard mission constraints (elevation, slope, rock abundance, communication geometry).

8.2 Phase 0 — Earth Validation (TRL 1–4, Duration: 5–8 years pre-launch)

Objective: Demonstrate complete integrated MABES system in Mars-simulated conditions on Earth.

Key activities:

1. Rapid Earth-chassis DBTL: Synechocystis/Synechococcus DBTL cycles to validate genetic modifications:
   · Radiation resistance (Dsup, Deinococcus repair genes)
   · Perchlorate reduction pathway (in B. subtilis)
   · Nitrogen fixation optimization (in Anabaena)
   · CO₂ fixation enhancement (RuBisCO variants, CCMs)
   · Cold adaptation (psychrophilic enzymes)
2. Transfer to Mars-deployment chassis: Validated modifications transferred to Chroococcidiopsis, Anabaena, and B. subtilis 168.
3. Partial-gravity simulation: Clinostat and random positioning machine (RPM) experiments to simulate 0.38g effects:
   · Cyanobacterial growth rates and morphology at 0.38g
   · Bioreactor fluid dynamics and mixing efficiency (Section 11.3)
   · CRISPR delivery efficiency at 0.38g
   · Monitor ESA BIORIDER results (Q3 2026 data release) for space-based 0.38g data
4. Perchlorate reduction kinetics measurement: Quantitative characterization of Strain C reduction rate in MGS-1 and MMS-2 simulants at Martian temperature ranges (0–25°C) and shielded UV conditions.
5. Full DBTL system integration test: Complete MABES system operated in Mars simulation chamber:
   · Pressure: 50–200 mbar
   · Temperature: −60°C to +20°C diurnal cycling
   · Radiation: Simulated GCR and UV spectrum
   · Latency: 48-minute round-trip delay enforced by network emulator
6. Bioreactor fluid dynamics optimization: Test modified sparger design (porous ceramic, 50 μm pore size) in clinostat-simulated 0.38g to validate restoration of 1g-equivalent mixing (Section 11.3).
7. Power budget validation: Measure actual power consumption of miniaturized biofoundry prototype and compare to Table 7.1 estimates.

