10. Novelty Contribution Statement

This dissertation makes the following specific claims of novelty, each distinguishing MABES from prior work in Mars synthetic biology, autonomous biofoundries, and ISRU architecture.

Novelty 1 — Latency-Tolerant Autonomous DBTL with Experimental Validation:
Existing autonomous biofoundry platforms (BioAutomata, iBioFAB, AI-native biofoundry, Ginkgo RAC) assume real-time or near-real-time human-in-the-loop availability for experiment approval, failure diagnosis, and safety response. MABES is the first formal architecture to design a DBTL system around 6–48 minute communication latency as a hard architectural constraint, requiring full onboard decision authority including safety-critical containment responses without Earth authorization. This claim is now supported by experimental ground-based validation (Patel et al., 2026) demonstrating that an autonomous biofoundry can operate effectively under simulated 48-minute latency.

Novelty 2 — Perchlorate Detoxification as Integrated Architectural Phase 0 with Quantified Kinetics:
Parallel research programs address perchlorate reduction (Rothschild et al., 2025; Arkin, 2024; NASA TechPort, 2025) and cyanobacterial Mars biology (Verseux et al., 2025; Billi et al., 2019) as separate endeavors. MABES integrates perchlorate detoxification as a mandatory prerequisite phase within the same autonomous DBTL system, with byproduct O₂ capture contributing to habitat life support. This integration is now supported by quantitative kinetics data under Martian temperature and UV conditions (Chen et al., 2026), enabling specific performance targets.

Novelty 3 — Three-Strain Synthetic Consortium with Orthogonal Obligate Commensalism for Dual-Purpose Stability and Containment:
Rather than engineering a single super-organism, MABES proposes a three-strain co-engineered consortium with explicit metabolic division of labor (O₂ production, N₂ fixation, soil detoxification). The consortium is stabilized by inter-strain synthetic auxotrophic dependencies — orthogonal obligate commensalism — that simultaneously serve as biocontainment Layer 5. This is the first Mars bio-engineering proposal to exploit obligate commensalism for the dual purposes of ecological stability and planetary protection. The approach is now experimentally validated in a cyanobacterial consortium (Lee et al., 2026).

Novelty 4 — Biological-Electrochemical ISRU Integration Framework with Quantitative Trade-Space:
MABES provides the first formal architecture specifying the complementary relationship between biological and electrochemical ISRU on Mars, with a quantitative energetic comparison table (Table 3.1) and a defined time-horizon handoff framework. Prior work treats these pathways as competing alternatives or addresses them independently.

Novelty 5 — Two-Phase Genetic Engineering Strategy with Demonstrated Direct CRISPR in Mars Chassis:
The explicit use of fast-growing, genetically tractable cyanobacterial chassis (Synechocystis, Synechococcus) for Earth DBTL validation, followed by transfer of validated modifications to Mars-deployment chassis (Chroococcidiopsis, Anabaena), is a pragmatic engineering strategy not previously formalized for an interplanetary synthetic biology context. This reduces Earth validation timelines by an estimated 60–70%. The strategy is now de-risked by the first demonstration of direct CRISPR-Cas12a editing in Chroococcidiopsis (Garcia et al., 2026).

Novelty 6 — Site Selection Framework Based on Orbital Nitrate Mapping:
MABES is the first Mars bio-engineering proposal to incorporate spatially resolved orbital nitrate distribution data (Smith et al., 2026) into a site selection framework, optimizing early-phase nitrogen availability and reducing pressure on biological nitrogen fixation.

Novelty 7 — Six-Layer Biocontainment Aligned with Emerging COSPAR Policy:
MABES specifies a six-layer biocontainment architecture (physical, synthetic auxotrophy, UV kill switch, quorum-sensing kill switch, orthogonal obligate commensalism, genetic barcoding) that anticipates the emerging COSPAR "contained use" framework for biological ISRU systems (Hedman et al., 2026; COSPAR, 2026).

