11. Limitations and Open Problems

11.1 Partial Gravity Biology

The effect of Martian gravity (0.38g) on cyanobacterial physiology, bioreactor fluid dynamics, and genetic engineering processes is poorly characterized. All laboratory experiments on MABES candidate organisms have been conducted at 1g or in microgravity (ISS experiments). The forthcoming ESA BIORIDER experiment data release (Q3 2026) will provide RNA-seq data on Chroococcidiopsis response to microgravity; partial gravity (0.38g) remains uncharacterized in spaceflight.

Phase 0 mitigation: Clinostat and random positioning machine (RPM) experiments to simulate 0.38g equivalent conditions. Specific measurements required:

· Cyanobacterial growth rate and morphology at 0.38g
· Bioreactor fluid dynamics (see Section 11.3)
· CRISPR ribonucleoprotein delivery efficiency via electroporation at 0.38g
· Gene expression changes (RNA-seq) under simulated 0.38g

11.2 Photosynthetic Productivity at Low Pressure

The Phase 1 assumption of 50–200 mbar bioreactor pressure enabling photosynthetically active cyanobacterial growth requires direct experimental validation. Chroococcidiopsis photosynthetic productivity specifically at 50–200 mbar has not been published in peer-reviewed literature. Phase 0 must measure this as a priority.

11.3 Bioreactor Fluid Dynamics at 0.38g

Computational fluid dynamics modeling (Nakamura et al., 2026) indicates that at 0.38g, bubble rise velocity is approximately 62% of the 1g value. This increases gas holdup by 35% and reduces mixing efficiency by 20% in standard sparger designs. Reduced mixing efficiency leads to:

· CO₂ depletion zones around cells
· O₂ accumulation (potentially inhibiting photosynthesis)
· Temperature gradients within the bioreactor

Proposed mitigation: Nakamura et al. (2026) propose a modified porous ceramic sparger with 50 μm pore size that generates smaller bubbles with higher surface-area-to-volume ratio, restoring mixing to 1g-equivalent levels at 0.38g. Phase 0 must test this sparger design in clinostat-simulated 0.38g conditions and measure mixing efficiency via tracer studies.

Power budget implication: The modified sparger may require slightly higher gas flow rates to achieve the same mass transfer, potentially increasing the mixing power budget by 10–20%. This is incorporated into the Table 7.1 estimate.

11.4 Long-Term Genetic Stability and Evolutionary Escape

Engineering organisms that remain stable through thousands of autonomous replication cycles without acquiring deleterious mutations or evolving escape from kill-switch circuits is an unsolved problem in synthetic biology. MABES proposes nanopore sequencing monitoring every 10 DBTL cycles, but the long-term evolutionary trajectories of organisms under Martian selection pressure — including the selective pressure imposed by the kill switches themselves (which select for loss-of-function mutations in the kill-switch circuitry) — cannot be predicted from current data.

Potential failure modes:

· Mutation or recombination inactivating the UV-responsive promoter or MazF coding sequence (Layer 3 escape)
· Evolution of quorum-sensing signal degradation or receptor desensitization (Layer 4 escape)
· Evolution of ncAA biosynthesis capability, bypassing synthetic auxotrophy (Layer 2 escape)
· Horizontal gene transfer between consortium strains, potentially transferring kill-switch-disabling mutations

Mitigation strategies:

· Redundant, orthogonal kill-switch mechanisms (already implemented)
· Periodic reseeding from validated spore stocks to reset evolutionary divergence
· Monitoring of kill-switch integrity via targeted nanopore sequencing of the relevant loci every 10 cycles
· AI-driven detection of evolutionary trends toward escape, triggering preemptive reseeding

Open problem: The evolutionary timescale for escape is unknown. This is the system's deepest scientific uncertainty.

11.5 Global Dust Storm Operational Continuity

The revised insolation reduction estimate of 60–70% during global dust storms (Wong et al., 2026) is less severe than the previously assumed 99%, but still represents a significant reduction in photosynthetic photon flux. Phase 2–3 organisms will experience reduced productivity and may enter dormancy if the storm persists for weeks.

Contingency planning required in Phase 0:

· Quantify the minimum photon flux required to maintain baseline metabolic activity and prevent population collapse.
· Design supplemental LED illumination system capable of providing 30% of clear-sky PAR to the ecological chambers during storm conditions.
· Validate power draw of supplemental system and ensure it remains within the Phase 2 power envelope (3–5 kWe).
· Test organism recovery after simulated 60–70% light reduction for 2–4 weeks (simulated storm duration).

11.6 Regolith Nutrient Depletion Dynamics

Long-term macronutrient and trace element dynamics in a semi-closed biological system fed by Martian regolith are not characterized. Specific concerns:

· Phosphorus: Present in Martian basalt as apatite, but bioavailability to cyanobacteria is unknown. Phosphorus is essential for ATP, nucleic acids, and membrane lipids.
· Iron: Abundant in Martian regolith, but primarily as Fe³⁺ oxides with low solubility. Cyanobacteria require iron for photosynthesis (cytochromes, ferredoxin) and nitrogen fixation (nitrogenase contains iron-molybdenum cofactor).
· Molybdenum: Essential cofactor for nitrogenase. Abundance in Martian regolith is poorly constrained. Molybdenum limitation could bottleneck nitrogen fixation.
· Sulfur: Present as sulfates (detected by multiple missions). Bioavailable, but may require reduction to sulfide for assimilation.

Phase 1 mitigation: Include ion chromatography and ICP-MS analysis of bioreactor medium to track nutrient concentrations over time. AI Core can adjust growth medium supplementation (from finite Earth-supplied reagent cache) based on detected depletions.

